        ],
        [
          "Regression",
          "Higher Education",
          "Self-Paced (degree-level progression)",
          "GPA (Grade Point Average, 4.0 scale)",
          "Predicted GPA at graduation",
          "1169",
          "811 courses (core and elective), focus on core courses from Mechanical and Aerospace Engineering at UCLA",
          "Admission Data,\nIn-Program Performance",
          "[Pre-college academic performance, course and grades obtained in each quarter in the program (using course clustering approach and excluding summer)]",
          "Every Quarter in the Program",
          "Authors perform course-clustering to identify what are the most relevant courses for each student. \n\nMore than pre-processing, learning is done in 2-ways: \n\nFirst, a set of base classifiers is trained offline, while a second tier of ensemble models follows online learning.\n\nFor a new student, the model makes a prediction for each course he/she is likely going to take and uses these as features to rpedict GPA.",
          "Ensemble-Based Progressive Prediction,\nLinear Regression, \nLogistic Regression,\nRandom Forest,\nKNN",
          "Holdout Method",
          "{Mean-Squared Error: EPP - All Benchmarks}",
          "The authors introduce a bilayer predictive model combining: (1) base predictors trained on course clusters and (2) a progressive ensemble layer that incorporates predictions over time. This allows  GPA prediction at each term. \n\nThe key innovation is the sequential ensemble that adapts using past and present predictions, making the model scalable and interpretable. \n\nCourse relevance is discovered via probabilistic matrix factorization, grouping similar courses to reduce noise and dimensionality. This outperforms traditional groupings (like prerequisites or same-department only). \n\nThe ensemble model outperforms all individual base predictors across terms, with MSE decreasing as student history grows. \n\nInsights include: (a) SAT Math is more predictive than HS GPA; (b) early prediction is feasible but less accurate; (c) course clusters can guide curriculum and advising. ",
          "Predictions limited to core courses only. Elective courses and course recommendations are not included. Performance generalization to other programs not tested. Data is from a single department and institution."
        ]
      ],
      "index": 11
    }
  ],
